docs.abstract: Largely outside of the limelight, athletes like Maya Moore, who helped win the freedom of Jonathan Irons in a questionable conviction, have led the charge for social change.
docs.snippet: Largely outside of the limelight, athletes like Maya Moore, who helped win the freedom of Jonathan Irons in a questionable conviction, have led the charge for social change.
docs.lead_paragraph: Still in her prime, Maya Moore sacrificed her career, stepping away as one of the greats in basketball for a long shot bid to help free a prisoner she was convinced had been wrongfully convicted.

headline.main: W.N.B.A. Star’s Role in Freeing Man From Prison Shows Female Athletes at Forefront
headline.print_headline: As Athletes Pursue Justice, Women Are a Force Without Fanfare

docs.abstract: He united people in shelters with those living on the streets, and he negotiated with city officials for greater support.
docs.snippet: He united people in shelters with those living on the streets, and he negotiated with city officials for greater support.
docs.lead_paragraph: Nikita Price’s father named him after Nikita Khrushchev, the Soviet premier, during the height of the Cold War, and it was just the sort of gesture Nikita would appreciate, his friends said: defiant, outraged, but with a sly wink at the absurdity of it.

headline.main: Nikita Price, Homeless Father Turned Advocate for Homeless, Dies at 63
headline.print_headline: Nikita Price, 63; Overcame Homelessness, and Fought It

docs.abstract: At this point in my career, as a senior leader, I welcome it when people engage me on the topic of race in the workplace.
docs.snippet: At this point in my career, as a senior leader, I welcome it when people engage me on the topic of race in the workplace.
docs.lead_paragraph: For senior company executives, appointments to public boards are one way to ease into retirement with purpose and prestige. But in a recent conversation I had with a 60-something white man, he lamented that the board opportunities he had expected and looked forward to are unlikely to materialize for him.

headline.main: I Was Told I Have Career Advantages ‘as a Black Woman.’ Here’s How I Replied.
headline.print_headline: I Was Told I Have Career Advantages ‘as a Black Woman’

docs.abstract: Facing decades in prison and a bail of at least $750,000, two former Minneapolis officers blamed Derek Chauvin, and a third has cooperated with investigators, their lawyers said.
docs.snippet: Facing decades in prison and a bail of at least $750,000, two former Minneapolis officers blamed Derek Chauvin, and a third has cooperated with investigators, their lawyers said.
docs.lead_paragraph: MINNEAPOLIS — Two of the former police officers charged with aiding and abetting in the killing of George Floyd turned on the senior officer accused in the case, making for an extraordinary court appearance on Thursday afternoon. A third officer was cooperating with the authorities, a sign that the four fired officers would not be presenting a united front.

headline.main: Officers Charged in George Floyd’s Death Not Likely to Present United Front
headline.print_headline: This Case Is Already Different:  The Police Are Breaking Ranks

byline.original: By Kim Barker, John Eligon, Richard A. Oppel Jr. and Matt Furber

docs.abstract: The police chief in LaGrange, Ga., who is white, apologized for the death of a young black man by a white mob in 1940.
docs.snippet: The police chief in LaGrange, Ga., who is white, apologized for the death of a young black man by a white mob in 1940.
docs.lead_paragraph: LaGRANGE, Ga. — Some people here had never heard about the lynching of Austin Callaway — about how, almost 77 years ago, he was dragged out of a jail cell by a band of masked white men, then shot and left for dead.

headline.main: Nearly 8 Decades Later, an Apology for a Lynching in Georgia
headline.print_headline: White Police Chief Apologizes for a 1940 Southern Lynching

byline.original: By Alan Blinder and Richard Fausset

docs.abstract: California officials seized a beachfront property from Willa and Charles Bruce in 1924. Los Angeles County returned it to their great-grandsons last year. Now they’re selling it back.
docs.snippet: California officials seized a beachfront property from Willa and Charles Bruce in 1924. Los Angeles County returned it to their great-grandsons last year. Now they’re selling it back.
docs.lead_paragraph: The great-grandchildren of a Black couple whose beachfront property in Southern California was seized by local officials in 1924, and returned to the family last year, will sell it back to Los Angeles County for nearly $20 million, an official said on Tuesday.

headline.main: L.A. County to Pay $20 Million for Land Once Seized From Black Family
headline.print_headline: Black Family to Get $20 Million Over Land Seizure From 1924
